      "name": "The Night Watch",
      "pid": "4",
      "text": "# The Night Watch\n## Rembrandt van Rijn, 1642\n\n![The Night Watch](assets/images/night_watch.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 2, Gallery of Honour, Room 2.8  \n**Size:** 363 cm √ó 437 cm (142.9 in √ó 172.0 in)  \n**Medium:** Oil on canvas  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-NIGHTWATCH-001\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/night_watch.mp3)\n\n### Overview\n\nRembrandt's masterpiece *The Night Watch* is one of the most famous paintings in the world. Officially titled *Militia Company of District II under the Command of Captain Frans Banninck Cocq*, this massive work depicts a city militia in dramatic motion.\n\n### What You're Seeing\n\nAt first glance, you might think this is a nighttime scene‚Äîhence the nickname \"The Night Watch.\" But it's actually a daytime scene! Centuries of varnish darkened the painting until its 1940s restoration revealed Rembrandt's true intention: a company of civic guards emerging from shadow into brilliant light.\n\n### Key Details to Notice\n\n**Captain Frans Banninck Cocq** (center, in black with red sash)\n- Notice his hand casting a shadow on his lieutenant's golden coat\n- This shadow proves Rembrandt's mastery of light\n\n**The Mysterious Girl** (left of center, in golden dress)\n- A young girl carrying a chicken (a symbol of the militia)\n- Still debated: Is she real or symbolic?\n\n**Hidden Elements:**\n- Count the figures‚Äîthere are 34 people!\n- Look for the hidden dog at lower right\n- Notice the pike, muskets, and spears creating depth\n\n### Recent History\n\nIn 2019, the largest ever research and conservation project on *The Night Watch* began, with restoration visible to museum visitors. The \"Operation Night Watch\" revealed new details and removed centuries of damage.\n\n### Artist: Rembrandt van Rijn (1606-1669)\n\nRembrandt was at the height of his career when he painted this revolutionary group portrait. Instead of the static, posed compositions typical of the era, Rembrandt showed the militia in dynamic action, capturing a moment of movement and drama.\n\n---\n\n**Next artwork:** The Milkmaid by Vermeer (Same room)",
