      "name": "The Milkmaid",
      "pid": "5",
      "text": "# The Milkmaid\n## Johannes Vermeer, c. 1660\n\n![The Milkmaid](assets/images/milkmaid.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 2, Gallery of Honour, Room 2.8  \n**Size:** 45.5 cm √ó 41 cm (17.9 in √ó 16.1 in)  \n**Medium:** Oil on canvas  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-MILKMAID-002\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/milkmaid.mp3)\n\n### Overview\n\nVermeer's *The Milkmaid* is a testament to finding beauty in everyday life. This small painting depicts a kitchen maid pouring milk, but Vermeer transforms this simple domestic scene into something monumental and timeless.\n\n### The Magic of Light\n\nVermeer was the master of light. Notice how natural light floods in from the window on the left, illuminating the maid, the bread, and especially that stream of milk. The way light catches the texture of the bread, the gleam of the brass, the rough wall‚Äîthis is Vermeer's genius.\n\n### What You're Looking At\n\n**The Maid:**\n- Sturdy, working-class woman (unusual for Dutch art)\n- Focused, concentrated on her task\n- Solid, monumental presence despite small canvas\n\n**The Still Life:**\n- Bread on the table (beautifully textured)\n- Blue and white Delftware jug\n- Stream of milk (incredibly realistic)\n- Foot warmer on the floor (copper, with coals)\n\n**Symbolic Elements:**\n- Bread: Daily sustenance, humble life\n- Milk: Purity, nourishment\n- Map on wall: The wider world beyond this moment\n- Delft tiles (bottom): Cupid figures (love/domestic virtue)\n\n### Vermeer's Technique\n\n**Pointillism Before Its Time:**\nLook closely at the bread‚ÄîVermeer used tiny dots of paint to create texture. This technique wouldn't be \"invented\" until the Impressionists 200 years later!\n\n**Camera Obscura:**\nScholars believe Vermeer used a camera obscura (early optical device) to achieve his incredibly precise perspective and light effects.\n\n### Historical Context\n\nIn Vermeer's time (Dutch Golden Age), the Netherlands was the wealthiest nation in Europe. Dutch art celebrated domestic life, commerce, and everyday virtues‚Äîquite different from the aristocratic subjects favored elsewhere.\n\nThis painting elevates a working servant to the status usually reserved for nobility or religious figures. The maid has dignity, focus, and presence.\n\n### Artist: Johannes Vermeer (1632-1675)\n\nVermeer lived his entire life in Delft, producing only about 35 paintings. He painted slowly, meticulously, and his work was largely forgotten until rediscovered in the 19th century. Today, his intimate scenes of domestic life are considered among the greatest achievements in Western art.\n\n---\n\n**Next artwork:** The Merry Drinker by Frans Hals (Room 2.9)",
