      "id": "merry_drinker",
      "name": "The Merry Drinker",
      "pid": "6",
      "text": "# The Merry Drinker\n## Frans Hals, c. 1628-1630\n\n![The Merry Drinker](assets/images/merry_drinker.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 2, Room 2.9  \n**Medium:** Oil on canvas  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-DRINKER-003\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/merry_drinker.mp3)\n\n### Overview\n\nFrans Hals captures pure joy in *The Merry Drinker*. This portrait radiates personality and spontaneity‚Äîyou can almost hear the man's laughter!\n\n### Revolutionary Technique\n\n**Loose Brushwork:**\nHals's technique was radical for his time. Notice the loose, visible brushstrokes‚Äîespecially in the clothing and lace collar. Get close to the painting: it looks almost abstract. Step back: it resolves into incredible realism.\n\nThis \"alla prima\" (wet-on-wet) technique wouldn't be embraced by mainstream art for another 200 years, with the Impressionists.\n\n### The Subject\n\n**A Man Enjoying Life:**\n- Raised glass (offering you a drink?)\n- Genuine smile (rare in Dutch portraits)\n- Fashionable dress (successful merchant class)\n- Direct eye contact (engaging the viewer)\n\n**Symbols:**\n- Wine glass: Pleasure, celebration\n- Rich clothing: Wealth, status\n- Direct gaze: Confidence, openness\n\n### Artist: Frans Hals (c. 1582-1666)\n\nFrans Hals was Haarlem's greatest portrait painter, known for capturing personality and spontaneity. While Rembrandt explored psychology and drama, Hals captured the spark of life‚Äîthe moment before the smile breaks into laughter.\n\nHals influenced everyone from Manet to Van Gogh, who studied his brushwork intensely.\n\n---\n\n**Next:** Rembrandt's Self-Portrait as Paul",
