      "id": "self_portrait_paul",
      "name": "Self-Portrait as the Apostle Paul",
      "pid": "7",
      "text": "# Self-Portrait as the Apostle Paul\n## Rembrandt van Rijn, 1661\n\n![Self-Portrait as Paul](assets/images/self_portrait_paul.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 2, Room 2.8  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-REMBRANDT-SELF-004\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/self_portrait_paul.mp3)\n\n### A Later Rembrandt\n\nThis self-portrait comes from Rembrandt's final decade‚Äîa period of personal tragedy but artistic triumph. By 1661, Rembrandt had faced bankruptcy, lost his beloved wife Saskia, and seen his reputation decline. Yet he painted some of his greatest masterpieces.\n\n### Why Saint Paul?\n\nRembrandt depicts himself as Paul the Apostle, holding a manuscript (Paul's epistles). This wasn't vanity‚Äîit was identification. Like Paul, Rembrandt had experienced success, suffering, and spiritual depth.\n\n**Notice:**\n- The sword (Paul's attribute as a martyr)\n- The manuscript (Paul's letters)\n- The aging face (Rembrandt was 55, weathered by life)\n- The penetrating gaze (wisdom, introspection)\n\n### Technique\n\nCompare this to *The Night Watch* (painted 19 years earlier). The brushwork here is looser, more expressive. Rembrandt builds up thick layers of paint (impasto), creating depth and luminosity. The face seems to emerge from darkness into light.\n\n---\n\n**More Rembrandt:** The Jewish Bride is nearby",
