      "id": "still_life",
      "name": "Still Life with Flowers and Fruit",
      "pid": "9",
      "text": "# Still Life with Flowers and Fruit\n## Jan van Huysum, c. 1715\n\n![Still Life](assets/images/still_life.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 1, Room 1.12  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-STILLLIFE-006\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/still_life.mp3)\n\n### Dutch Botanical Perfection\n\nJan van Huysum was the most celebrated still life painter of his generation, commanding enormous prices for works like this. Look closely‚Äîyou can see why.\n\n### Impossible Perfection\n\nHere's the secret: These flowers could never bloom together. Van Huysum painted them over months, as each species came into season. Tulips in spring, roses in summer, peonies at different times. The painting is a botanical fantasy‚Äînature perfected beyond reality.\n\n### Symbolic Language\n\n**Every element has meaning:**\n- Flowers: Beauty, fragility of life\n- Insects: Natural cycle, decay\n- Fruit: Abundance, sensuality\n- Dewdrops: Purity, freshness\n\nDutch viewers read these paintings like books, finding moral lessons and spiritual truths in bouquets.\n\n### The Market\n\nDuring the Dutch Golden Age, the Netherlands dominated world trade in flowers, especially tulips. A painting like this celebrated Dutch botanical expertise and global commerce.\n\n---\n\n**Next:** The Threatened Swan",
