      "name": "The Battle of Waterloo",
      "pid": "15",
      "text": "# The Battle of Waterloo\n## Jan Willem Pieneman, 1824\n\n![Battle of Waterloo](assets/images/battle_waterloo.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 0, Room 0.13  \n**Size:** 567 cm √ó 823 cm (massive!)  \n**Medium:** Oil on canvas  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-WATERLOO-010\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/battle_waterloo.mp3)\n\n### Epic Scale\n\nAt over 8 meters wide, this is one of the largest paintings in the Rijksmuseum. Pieneman depicts the decisive moment of the Battle of Waterloo (June 18, 1815), when Napoleon's final defeat secured peace in Europe.\n\n### The Scene\n\nYou're looking at the battlefield near Brussels at approximately 4 PM. The Duke of Wellington (center, on white horse) has just received word that Prussian reinforcements are arriving. The battle's outcome is about to turn decisively against Napoleon.\n\n**Key Figures:**\n- **Duke of Wellington** (center, white horse, bicorne hat): British commander\n- **William, Prince of Orange** (wounded, being carried): Dutch heir, future King William II\n- **Lord Uxbridge** (right foreground): British cavalry commander\n- **Wounded soldiers** throughout: The human cost of victory\n\n### Historical Context\n\nWaterloo ended 23 years of nearly continuous warfare that had engulfed Europe since the French Revolution. This Dutch commission celebrated the Netherlands' role in Napoleon's defeat and the restoration of Dutch independence under the House of Orange.\n\n### The Dutch Perspective\n\nNotice how Prince William is prominently featured despite his relatively minor role in the actual battle. Pieneman was painting Dutch patriotism as much as historical accuracy. The painting glorifies Dutch courage and sacrifice in the coalition victory.\n\n### Artistic Achievement\n\nPieneman worked from sketches made on the actual battlefield shortly after the battle. He interviewed participants and studied uniforms and equipment to achieve remarkable accuracy in detail‚Äîeven if the composition is somewhat romanticized.\n\n**Details to notice:**\n- The smoke and chaos of battle\n- Individual soldiers' expressions (fear, exhaustion, determination)\n- The variety of uniforms (British, Dutch, Belgian, Nassau)\n- Wounded horses (the forgotten casualties)\n- The dramatic sky and lighting\n\n### Legacy\n\nThis painting became an icon of 19th-century Dutch nationalism. It was displayed prominently in the Rijksmuseum from its opening in 1885, reminding visitors of the Netherlands' role in shaping modern Europe.\n\n---\n\n**Next:** Dutch maritime power through an incredible ship model",
