      "pid": "16",
      "text": "# Model of the Warship 'Amsterdam'\n## Anonymous Dutch Shipwright, c. 1750\n\n![Warship Model](assets/images/warship_model.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 0, Room 0.3  \n**Scale:** 1:48 (detailed ship model)  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-WARSHIP-011\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/warship_model.mp3)\n\n### Dutch Maritime Power\n\nDuring the 17th and 18th centuries, the Netherlands was a global maritime superpower. This exquisitely detailed ship model represents a Dutch warship from the height of Dutch naval dominance.\n\n### What You're Looking At\n\nThis isn't a toy‚Äîit's a working model built to exact specifications. Shipwrights created these models for multiple purposes:\n\n**Design & Planning:**\n- Scale models allowed naval architects to test designs before construction\n- Clients (the Admiralty, VOC) could approve designs\n- Helped calculate material costs and construction time\n\n**Prestige & Display:**\n- Demonstrated Dutch craftsmanship and technological superiority\n- Displayed in guild halls and government buildings\n- Diplomatic gifts to foreign courts\n\n### The Dutch Fleet\n\nAt its peak (mid-1600s), the Dutch Republic possessed the world's largest merchant fleet‚Äîmore ships than England, France, and Spain combined. The Dutch East India Company (VOC) maintained its own navy to protect trade routes to Asia.\n\n**Types of Dutch Ships:**\n- **Warships** (like this model): Heavily armed, 50-80 cannons\n- **Merchant ships** (fluyts): Cargo-optimized, lightly armed\n- **VOC ships** (Indiamen): Large armed merchants for Asian trade\n\n### Incredible Detail\n\nLook closely at this model:\n- **Rigging**: Every rope (hundreds!) individually threaded\n- **Cannons**: Miniature working replicas\n- **Deck details**: Tiny hatches, railings, capstans\n- **Hull**: Carved planking, authentic painting\n- **Figurehead**: Intricately carved\n\nShipwrights spent months creating models like this, using the same woods and techniques as full-size ships.\n\n### The Age of Sail\n\nThese ships dominated warfare for centuries:\n- Speed: Up to 12 knots with favorable wind\n- Crew: 400-500 sailors and marines\n- Range: Could remain at sea for months\n- Firepower: Broadside of 30+ cannons\n\nNaval battles were floating artillery duels, with ships maneuvering to deliver devastating broadsides while avoiding enemy fire.\n\n### Economic Foundation\n\nDutch wealth during the Golden Age rested on seapower. Ships like this protected trade routes, secured colonies, and projected Dutch influence globally‚Äîfrom Indonesia to New Amsterdam (New York), from Brazil to Taiwan.\n\n---\n\n**Final stop:** An extraordinary Dutch dollhouse",
