      "name": "Dutch Dollhouse of Petronella Oortman",
      "pid": "17",
      "text": "# The Dutch Dollhouse of Petronella Oortman\n## Various Craftsmen, c. 1686-1710\n\n![Dutch Dollhouse](assets/images/dutch_dollhouse.jpg)\n\n**Location:** Floor 0, Room 0.6  \n**Size:** 255 cm high √ó 190 cm wide  \n**QR Code:** RIJKS-DOLLHOUSE-012\n\n[audio](assets/audio/en/dutch_dollhouse.mp3)\n\n### Not for Children\n\nThis isn't a child's toy‚Äîit's a wealthy woman's most prized possession. Petronella Oortman (1656-1716), wife of a rich Amsterdam silk merchant, spent a fortune assembling this miniature mansion. Contemporary accounts suggest it cost as much as an actual Amsterdam canal house!\n\n### What You're Seeing\n\nThis cabinet dollhouse represents an idealized wealthy Dutch home from around 1700, displayed behind glass doors like a piece of furniture.\n\n**Three Floors:**\n\n**Top Floor: Private Chambers**\n- Bedroom with canopied bed (tiny embroidered linens!)\n- Linen room (miniature towels and sheets)\n- Lying-in room (for childbirth)\n\n**Middle Floor: Reception Rooms**\n- Best parlor (formal entertaining)\n- Music room (tiny paintings on walls)\n- Nursery (miniature cradle)\n\n**Ground Floor: Working Areas**\n- Kitchen (copper pots, working fireplace)\n- Storage rooms\n- Basement (food supplies)\n\n### Extraordinary Craftsmanship\n\nEvery single object was hand-crafted by master artisans:\n\n**Paintings:** Real artists created miniature artworks for the walls\n**Furniture:** Master cabinetmakers built scaled pieces\n**Silver:** Goldsmiths created tiny utensils (actually functional!)\n**Porcelain:** Delftware miniatures from actual Delft factories\n**Textiles:** Embroidered linens, woven rugs‚Äîall to scale\n**Books:** Tiny leather-bound volumes with actual pages\n\nLook closely: That's real gold leaf, actual silk damask, genuine pearls on the miniature costumes.\n\n### Social History\n\nThis dollhouse is an incredible document of Golden Age domestic life:\n\n**What it reveals:**\n- How wealthy Dutch families lived\n- Interior decoration trends of the period\n- Gender roles (women's domain: the household)\n- Consumer culture (displaying wealth through possessions)\n- Dutch values (order, cleanliness, prosperity)\n\n### The Cost\n\nPetronella kept meticulous records of her purchases. Some examples:\n- Miniature silver tea service: 6 guilders (a skilled worker's weekly wage)\n- Tiny paintings: 20-30 guilders each\n- Entire dollhouse: 20,000-30,000 guilders (equal to an actual house!)\n\nWhy so expensive? Because she commissioned the finest craftsmen in Amsterdam to create each object to her exact specifications.\n\n### Prestige Object\n\nDollhouses like this served multiple purposes:\n- **Status symbol:** Demonstrating wealth and taste\n- **Educational tool:** Teaching daughters household management\n- **Artistic showcase:** Displaying knowledge of art and design\n- **Conversation piece:** Entertaining guests\n- **Legacy project:** Something to pass down through generations\n\n### Survival and Preservation\n\nRemarkably, this 300+ year-old object survives almost intact. Most dollhouses were played with, damaged, or broken up. Petronella's dollhouse survived because it was always a display piece, carefully maintained by successive generations.\n\nThe Rijksmuseum acquired it in 1876, and it has captivated visitors ever since‚Äîperhaps the museum's most beloved object for children and adults alike.\n\n### What It Teaches Us\n\nThis dollhouse embodies the Dutch Golden Age:\n- Wealth from global trade\n- Obsession with domestic virtue\n- Celebration of craftsmanship\n- Art collecting as status symbol\n- Attention to detail and quality\n\nIt's a complete world in miniature‚Äîand a window into a vanished way of life.\n\n---\n\n**Congratulations!** You've completed all 12 artworks on the tour.",
